The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | DAY I HIGHLIGHTS
                                                                                                                                                                                                     DAY I HIGHLIGHTS
                      
	V.V.S. Laxman is the first Indian and the 10th cricketer overall not to captain his team despite playing 100 Tests  the other nine being Shane Warne, Mark Waugh, Glenn McGrath, Ian Healy, David Boon, Justin Langer, Graham Thorpe, Muttiah Muralitharan and Chaminda Vaas.         
	Laxman became the most-capped Test player from Hyderabad. Mohammed Azharuddin had appeared in 99 Tests.         
	The Vidarbha Cricket Association Stadium, Jamtha, became the 99th venue to host a Test match. It also became Indias 20th Test venue. This stadium is now the second Test venue in the city of Nagpur. Chennai and Lucknow are the other Indian cities that have two Test grounds while Mumbai is the only city to host Tests in three grounds.         
	The VCA Stadium also became the third Indian venue to host a Test match as the first ever match to be played there. The other two being University Ground, Lucknow (Ind vs Pak, Oct. 1952) and Gujarat Stadium, Ahmedabad (Ind vs WI, Nov. 1983). India lost the Test on both the occasions.         
	Jason Krejza and Murali Vijay Krishna became the 403rd and 260th players to represent Australia and India respectively in Tests.         
	Vijay is also the 24th player from the state of Tamil Nadu to play Tests for India. The last to do so being Dinesh Karthik.         
	Rahul Dravid has not scored a duck since his duck for the World XI vs Australia in Sydney 2005-06. His last duck for India in a Test was vs Bangladesh in Dhaka 2004-05.         
	By playing a Test at the VCA Stadium, Sachin Tendulkar has played in 56 different venues. The closest to this is Mohammed Azharuddin, who played at 48 grounds, while Kapil Dev and Inzamam-ul Haq have played at 47 each.         
	By scoring his 52nd Test 50, Sachin Tendulkar now has 91 scores of 50 or more in Test cricket (39 hundreds+52 fifties). He goes past Alan Border who has 90 (27 hundreds, 63 fifties).         
	Tendulkar now has been involved in 69 century stands. He went past Australias ricky Ponting, who has 68. Rahul Dravid with 72, however, has been involved in most century stands.         
	Tendulkars hundred was his 17th at home. He now has the most hundreds on Indian soil.               
